importance of providing infection prevention training for
health works to increase their knowledge about MDR-TB.
Our study also found that only one-fourth of health
works had good self-reported practice towards the
prevention and control of MDR-TB. This low MDR-TB
prevention and control practice among health workers
is particularly risky in high TB burden countries such as
Ethiopia because outbreaks of MDR-TB may occur in the
hospitals. A high rate of hospital transmission of MDR-TB
has been reported in previous studies.
With regard to the practice of referring to the treat-
ment guidelines, it is only one-third (32.6%) of partic-
ipants had access to the MDR-TB guideline in the
hospitals; and less than a third (29.17%) of participants
referred to these guidelines while treating the patients.
